50|$|The {{occupying power}} called it <b>counter-sabotage,</b> but the Danes quickly adopted the name schalburgtage. In fact, {{most of the}} schalburgtage {{was carried out by}} the Peter group, most of whose members were also members of the Schalburg Corps.|$|E
50|$|The unit, Brigade de Recherches et de Contra-Sabotage (BRCS)) ("Intelligence & <b>Counter-Sabotage</b> Brigade") {{was dubbed}} the Commando Colonel Sérot in the slain Colonel's honor. Meyer's {{father had been}} Sérot's friend and Sérot mentored Meyer when they worked {{together}} in the Resistance.|$|E
5000|$|<b>Counter-sabotage,</b> {{defined by}} Webster's Dictionary, is [...] "counterintelligence {{designed}} {{to detect and}} counteract sabotage." [...] The United States Department of Defense definition, found in the Dictionary of Military and Associated Terms, is [...] "action designed to detect and counteract sabotage. See also counterintelligence".|$|E
